{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01DwWcNXZ4dgtoQhoim6P8Dk","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Installation\n     2→\n     3→This document covers the various ways to install Cloche on your machine.\n     4→\n     5→## Prerequisites\n     6→\n     7→All installation methods require:\n     8→\n     9→- **Docker** — Cloche runs workflows in containers\n    10→- **Git** — result extraction uses git worktrees\n    11→\n    12→## Build from Source\n    13→\n    14→Clone the repository, build the binaries and Docker image, and install them:\n    15→\n    16→```\n    17→git clone https://github.com/cloche-dev/cloche.git\n    18→cd cloche\n    19→make install\n    20→```\n    21→\n    22→`make install` builds all three binaries (`cloche`, `cloched`, `cloche-agent`),\n    23→builds the `cloche-agent:latest` Docker image, installs the binaries to\n    24→`~/.local/bin/`, and starts the daemon. You can change the install prefix:\n    25→\n    26→```\n    27→make install PREFIX=/usr/local\n    28→```\n    29→\n    30→Make sure the install prefix is on your `PATH`:\n    31→\n    32→```\n    33→export PATH=\"$HOME/.local/bin:$PATH\"\n    34→```\n    35→\n    36→### Build Requirements\n    37→\n    38→- Go 1.25+\n    39→\n    40→## `go install`\n    41→\n    42→If you have Go installed, you can install the binaries directly:\n    43→\n    44→```\n    45→go install github.com/cloche-dev/cloche/cmd/cloche@latest\n    46→go install github.com/cloche-dev/cloche/cmd/cloched@latest\n    47→go install github.com/cloche-dev/cloche/cmd/cloche-agent@latest\n    48→```\n    49→\n    50→This places the binaries in `$GOPATH/bin` (or `$HOME/go/bin` by default).\n    51→\n    52→You still need to build the Docker image separately. Clone the repository and\n    53→run:\n    54→\n    55→```\n    56→git clone https://github.com/cloche-dev/cloche.git\n    57→cd cloche\n    58→make docker-build\n    59→```\n    60→\n    61→## Pre-built Release Binaries (Planned)\n    62→\n    63→> **Note:** Pre-built release binaries are not yet available. This section\n    64→> describes the planned installation method for when releases are published.\n    65→\n    66→Download pre-built binaries from the\n    67→[GitHub Releases](https://github.com/cloche-dev/cloche/releases) page. Each\n    68→release will include archives for common platforms (Linux amd64, Linux arm64,\n    69→macOS amd64, macOS arm64).\n    70→\n    71→```\n    72→# Example: Linux amd64\n    73→curl -LO https://github.com/cloche-dev/cloche/releases/latest/download/cloche-linux-amd64.tar.gz\n    74→tar xzf cloche-linux-amd64.tar.gz\n    75→sudo install cloche cloched cloche-agent /usr/local/bin/\n    76→```\n    77→\n    78→You still need to build the Docker image. Clone the repo and run\n    79→`make docker-build`:\n    80→\n    81→```\n    82→git clone https://github.com/cloche-dev/cloche.git\n    83→cd cloche\n    84→make docker-build\n    85→```\n    86→\n    87→## Homebrew (macOS / Linux) (Planned)\n    88→\n    89→> **Note:** A Homebrew tap is not yet published. This section describes the\n    90→> planned installation method.\n    91→\n    92→```\n    93→brew tap cloche-dev/tap\n    94→brew install cloche\n    95→```\n    96→\n    97→This will install all three binaries. You will still need the Docker image —\n    98→the formula will print post-install instructions for building or pulling it.\n    99→\n   100→## Verifying the Installation\n   101→\n   102→After installing, verify that everything works:\n   103→\n   104→```\n   105→# Check versions\n   106→cloche --version\n   107→\n   108→# Start the daemon (if not already running)\n   109→cloched &\n   110→\n   111→# Build the agent image\n   112→make docker-build\n   113→\n   114→# Run a quick test from any git repository with a .cloche/ directory\n   115→cloche list\n   116→```\n   117→\n   118→## Upgrading\n   119→\n   120→To upgrade an existing installation, repeat your original installation method.\n   121→If you built from source:\n   122→\n   123→```\n   124→cd cloche\n   125→git pull\n   126→make install\n   127→```\n   128→\n   129→The `make install` target stops the running daemon, installs the new binaries,\n   130→and restarts the daemon automatically.\n   131→\n   132→## Next Steps\n   133→\n   134→- [Usage guide](USAGE.md) — quick start, CLI reference, and workflow setup\n   135→- [Workflow DSL reference](workflows.md) — full syntax for `.cloche` files\n   136→- [How to set up Claude Code](agent-setup-claude.md) — container setup for Claude\n   137→- [How to set up Codex](agent-setup-codex.md) — container setup for Codex\n   138→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01JUnpJzSHuhmadkgcFGRrK6","session_id":"a1496100-58bb-4933-86a8-269a722f19f5","uuid":"71a2f99a-9d15-4c98-930d-09d8bc8fb124"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01WizuGDsXMmKYoscorpfdym","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Safety Guide\n     2→\n     3→This document covers good practices for using Cloche securely. The central concern is\n     4→the **Lethal Trifecta** of LLM-powered agent usage: when a system simultaneously has\n     5→(1) access to private data, (2) exposure to untrusted content, and (3) the ability to\n     6→communicate externally, it becomes vulnerable to prompt injection attacks that can\n     7→exfiltrate sensitive information. Cloche's architecture is designed to let you break this\n     8→trifecta, but only if you configure it correctly.\n     9→\n    10→## The Lethal Trifecta\n    11→\n    12→Any system that combines all three of the following is at risk:\n    13→\n    14→1. **Access to private data** — The agent can read source code, credentials, API keys,\n    15→   internal documentation, or customer data.\n    16→2. **Exposure to untrusted content** — The agent processes inputs that an attacker could\n    17→   influence: issue descriptions, pull request comments, dependency READMEs, web pages,\n    18→   or fetched API responses.\n    19→3. **Ability to communicate externally** — The agent can make HTTP requests, send emails,\n    20→   push to remote repositories, or otherwise transmit data outside the local environment.\n    21→\n    22→When all three are present, a prompt injection hidden in untrusted content can instruct\n    23→the agent to exfiltrate private data through the external communication channel. The\n    24→defense is to remove at least one leg of the trifecta.\n    25→\n    26→Cloche helps by isolating agent work inside containers where you control filesystem\n    27→access and network egress. But the host side of Cloche has no such isolation — host-side\n    28→agent steps run with the daemon's full OS privileges. The recommendations below focus on\n    29→keeping host-side exposure minimal and container-side access locked down.\n    30→\n    31→## Minimize Host-Side Agent Usage\n    32→\n    33→Host workflows (those with a `host { }` block) run directly on the host machine. Agent\n    34→steps in host workflows inherit the daemon's permissions: full filesystem, full network,\n    35→all environment variables.\n    36→\n    37→**Prefer container workflows for agent work.** The `workflow` step type in host workflows\n    38→dispatches work to an isolated container. Use it:\n    39→\n    40→```\n    41→workflow \"main\" {\n    42→  step prepare-prompt {\n    43→    run = \".cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh\"\n    44→    results = [success, fail]\n    45→  }\n    46→\n    47→  step develop {\n    48→    workflow_name = \"develop\"\n    49→    results = [success, fail]\n    50→  }\n    51→\n    52→  prepare-prompt:success -> develop\n    53→  prepare-prompt:fail    -> abort\n    54→  develop:success        -> done\n    55→  develop:fail           -> abort\n    56→}\n    57→```\n    58→\n    59→In this pattern, the host workflow uses a *script* step (deterministic, no LLM) to\n    60→prepare the prompt and a *workflow* step to dispatch it to a container. No agent step\n    61→runs on the host.\n    62→\n    63→**If you must use host-side agent steps**, limit what the agent can access:\n    64→\n    65→- Run the daemon under a dedicated service account with restricted filesystem\n    66→  permissions rather than your personal user account.\n    67→- Avoid setting broad environment variables (cloud credentials, database URLs) in the\n    68→  daemon's environment. Only export what is strictly needed.\n    69→- Keep host workflows simple — use them for orchestration (scripts and workflow dispatch),\n    70→  not for direct agent work.\n    71→\n    72→## Network Allowlisting\n    73→\n    74→Containers should have the minimum network access needed for their task. The workflow DSL\n    75→accepts a `network_allow` list in the `container {}` block to declare intended egress\n    76→restrictions:\n    77→\n    78→```\n    79→workflow \"develop\" {\n    80→  container {\n    81→    image         = \"my-project:latest\"\n    82→    network_allow = [\"api.anthropic.com\", \"github.com\"]\n    83→  }\n    84→\n    85→  step implement {\n    86→    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    87→    results = [success, fail]\n    88→  }\n    89→\n    90→  implement:success -> done\n    91→  implement:fail    -> abort\n    92→}\n    93→```\n    94→\n    95→> **Note:** `network_allow` is currently parsed by the DSL but not enforced at runtime —\n    96→> containers run with unrestricted network access. Until enforcement is implemented, use\n    97→> the Docker-level controls described below to actually restrict egress. Declaring\n    98→> `network_allow` in your workflow is still recommended as documentation of intent and to\n    99→> be ready when enforcement lands.\n   100→\n   101→A good allowlist includes only:\n   102→\n   103→- The AI provider API endpoint (e.g. `api.anthropic.com`)\n   104→- Your git remote for pushing results (e.g. `github.com`)\n   105→- Language-specific package registries only if the workflow installs dependencies\n   106→\n   107→Everything else — documentation sites, third-party APIs, general internet — should be\n   108→excluded unless the task specifically requires it. The agent may be less capable without\n   109→web access, but the security tradeoff is worth it for tasks involving sensitive code.\n   110→\n   111→### Docker Network Isolation\n   112→\n   113→Since `network_allow` is not yet enforced, Docker-level network restrictions are\n   114→currently the primary mechanism for limiting container egress. Configure them in your\n   115→project's Dockerfile or via Docker runtime options:\n   116→\n   117→**Drop all network by default.** If your workflow does not need any network (e.g. pure\n   118→code editing with tests), override the container's network at the Docker level:\n   119→\n   120→```dockerfile\n   121→# In your .cloche/Dockerfile — no network-dependent steps\n   122→FROM cloche-base:latest\n   123→# Install all dependencies at build time so no runtime downloads needed\n   124→COPY requirements.txt .\n   125→RUN pip install -r requirements.txt\n   126→```\n   127→\n   128→When all dependencies are baked into the image, the container needs no outbound access\n   129→except for the AI provider API.\n   130→\n   131→**Restrict DNS resolution.** Containers use Docker's embedded DNS by default. For\n   132→tighter control, you can specify DNS servers that only resolve your allowlisted domains,\n   133→or use a DNS-based firewall.\n   134→\n   135→**Avoid `--privileged` and `--cap-add`.** Cloche containers do not need elevated\n   136→capabilities. The base image runs as an unprivileged `agent` user. Never run Cloche\n   137→containers with `--privileged` or add capabilities like `NET_ADMIN` unless you have a\n   138→specific, justified need.\n   139→\n   140→## Filesystem Isolation\n   141→\n   142→Cloche containers get a *copy* of your project, not a bind mount. This is a deliberate\n   143→security choice:\n   144→\n   145→- The agent cannot modify your host filesystem directly.\n   146→- Changes are only extracted back via `docker cp` to a git branch after the run\n   147→  completes.\n   148→- You review the changes in a branch before merging.\n   149→\n   150→**Keep this model intact.** Avoid using `CLOCHE_EXTRA_MOUNTS` to bind-mount sensitive\n   151→host directories into containers. If you need additional files in the container, prefer\n   152→the `.cloche/overrides/` mechanism, which copies files at container start time.\n   153→\n   154→**Audit override files.** Everything in `.cloche/overrides/` is applied on top of\n   155→`/workspace/` in the container. Do not place credentials or sensitive configuration in\n   156→this directory — it is checked into version control.\n   157→\n   158→## Credential Handling\n   159→\n   160→**API keys.** The `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` environment variable is automatically passed into\n   161→containers. Other environment variables must be explicitly passed via `CLOCHE_EXTRA_ENV`.\n   162→Only pass what the agent needs.\n   163→\n   164→**Git credentials.** Cloche copies `~/.claude` and `~/.claude.json` into containers for\n   165→agent authentication. These are copied (not mounted) so concurrent runs do not conflict.\n   166→Be aware that these files are present in the container filesystem during the run.\n   167→\n   168→**Do not bake secrets into Docker images.** Use environment variables or runtime\n   169→injection rather than embedding API keys, tokens, or passwords in your Dockerfile or\n   170→`.cloche/overrides/`.\n   171→\n   172→```\n   173→# Good: pass at runtime\n   174→CLOCHE_EXTRA_ENV=DATABASE_URL=postgres://... cloche run develop\n   175→\n   176→# Bad: in Dockerfile\n   177→ENV DATABASE_URL=postgres://...\n   178→```\n   179→\n   180→## Prompt Hygiene\n   181→\n   182→The content of prompts is the primary vector for injection attacks. Untrusted content\n   183→that reaches an agent's prompt can instruct it to take unintended actions.\n   184→\n   185→**Separate trusted and untrusted content.** Prompt templates in `.cloche/prompts/` are\n   186→trusted — you write and review them. User requests (task descriptions, issue bodies) are\n   187→untrusted — they come from external sources. Cloche's prompt assembly concatenates these,\n   188→so the agent sees both. Keep the trusted template's instructions clear and explicit to\n   189→reduce the chance of injection overriding them.\n   190→\n   191→**Validate external inputs in script steps.** Use host-side script steps to sanitize or\n   192→filter task descriptions before passing them to agent steps. For example,\n   193→`.cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh` can strip HTML, limit length, or reject suspicious\n   194→patterns before writing to `$CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT`.\n   195→\n   196→**Limit feedback content.** The `feedback = \"true\"` step config includes previous output\n   197→logs in the prompt. If those logs contain content from untrusted sources (e.g. test\n   198→output that includes user-supplied data), this is another injection surface. Only enable\n   199→feedback when needed.\n   200→\n   201→## Review Before Merge\n   202→\n   203→Cloche extracts results to git branches, not directly to your main branch. Always review\n   204→the agent's changes before merging:\n   205→\n   206→- Check for unexpected file modifications outside the task scope.\n   207→- Look for new dependencies, network calls, or credential usage that the task did not\n   208→  require.\n   209→- Verify that no files were added that could serve as persistence mechanisms (cron jobs,\n   210→  git hooks, CI config changes).\n   211→\n   212→This review step is your final safeguard. Automated agents are powerful but not\n   213→infallible — treat their output with the same scrutiny you would give any external\n   214→contribution.\n   215→\n   216→## Summary\n   217→\n   218→| Risk | Mitigation |\n   219→|------|-----------|\n   220→| Host-side agent has full access | Use container workflows for agent steps; keep host workflows to scripts and dispatch |\n   221→| Unrestricted network in container | Declare `network_allow`; enforce with Docker-level network controls until runtime enforcement lands |\n   222→| Sensitive files in container | Rely on copy-based isolation; avoid bind mounts; audit overrides |\n   223→| Credentials leaking | Pass via env vars at runtime, not in images or overrides |\n   224→| Prompt injection | Sanitize untrusted inputs in script steps; keep prompt templates explicit |\n   225→| Malicious agent output | Review branches before merging; check for unexpected changes |\n   226→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01JUnpJzSHuhmadkgcFGRrK6","session_id":"a1496100-58bb-4933-86a8-269a722f19f5","uuid":"fb0faf9e-d895-413a-b2c8-56435ed1d9a1"}
